<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title> Try It Yourself </title>
   <style type="text/css">
      p:lang(en) > q {
         color: blue;
         quotes: '\201C' '\201D' '\2018' '\2019';
      }
      p:lang(fr) > q {
         color: red;
         quotes: '« ' ' »';
      }
      p:lang(de) > q {
         color: green;
         quotes: '»' '«' '\2039' '\203A';
      }
   </style>
</head>
<body>
   <p> The <b>:lang(&lt;language-code&gt;)</b> CSS pseudo-class matches elements based on the language they are determined to be in. </p>
   
   <h3> Example: </h3>
   <p lang="en"><q> Hello World! I love Codeliber! </q></p>
   <p lang="fr"><q> Hello World! I love Codeliber! </q></p>
   <p lang="de"><q> Hello World! I love Codeliber! </q></p>
   <p> In the example above we use the child combinator to select the <b>&lt;q&gt;</b> elements inside the <b>&lt;p&gt;</b> elements then we specified the quotation marks using the <b>quotes</b> CSS property. </p>
</body>
</html>